{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RLkmSfGtUpPbtT2D1RtDDr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the scenario better. Looking at the test.yaml, the fault injection (in the precondition `apply` step) does:\n1. Scales down the StatefulSet to `fault_expected_nodes` (2) replicas\n2. Waits for pod `es-cluster-2` to be deleted\n3. Deletes the PVC `data-es-cluster-2`\n4. Scales back up to `expected_node_count` (3) replicas\n5. Waits until `fault_expected_nodes` (2) nodes appear in `_cat/nodes`\nThe fault essentially recreates es-cluster-2 with a fresh empty PVC, but the seed_hosts ConfigMap gets corrupted with incorrect DNS entries pointing to `.default.svc.cluster.local` instead of the correct namespace format that's defined in the actual configmap.yaml resource.\n\nLooking at the precondition logs, the probe checked for running pods and found 9, which means the apply step was skipped since it only runs on probe failure. So the fault wasn't freshly injected here—it must have come from an earlier stage, and the precondition just verified the cluster was already in that broken state.\n\nBut now examining the actual cluster state, I'm seeing 5 nodes in `_cat/nodes` when the test expects only 2 nodes to remain after the fault. This mismatch suggests either the fault wasn't properly applied in this pipeline run, or a previous stage set up the cluster differently than expected. The probe succeeded with 9 running pods, which means the `apply` step should have executed rather than been skipped—I need to clarify the logic of `on_probe_fail: skip` to understand whether a successful probe triggers the fault injection or prevents it. non-zero exit code means the probe succeeded, so the apply should run. The apply step is scaling down the Elasticsearch deployment using kubectl, which is the fault injection part of the precondition. Writing shell commands...\n\nThe precondition check shows 9 running pods, but I'm noticing the apply commands aren't appearing in the precondition log—only the probe output and seed data. This suggests the apply step may not have actually executed, which would explain why we're still seeing the full cluster size rather than the reduced fault state. So the es_env_ready apply was skipped because the probe succeeded (returned 9 running pods), meaning the system was already in the target state. The `on_probe_fail: skip` directive actually inverts the normal behavior—instead of running apply when the probe fails, it skips the entire unit, which contradicts what I'd expect from the naming.\n\nLet me reconsider how the probe works: `grep -c Running` returns the count of matches, with exit code 0 if there's at least one match and exit code 1 if there are none. So when pods are running, the probe passes (exit 0) and apply runs to inject the fault, but when pods aren't running, the probe fails (exit 1) and the unit is skipped entirely rather than attempting setup from scratch.\n\nLooking back at the precondition log, I see the probe command executed and returned 9 running pods, which means the probe passed—so the apply should have run, but I'm not seeing those apply commands in the log output, only the initial probe result. I think I've been misinterpreting the `on_probe_fail: skip` logic. If the probe passes (9 pods running), that means the environment is already ready, so we skip the apply step since there's nothing to set up. The apply only runs when the probe fails, indicating the environment needs to be initialized. So the precondition log showing just the probe result without an apply makes sense—the condition was already satisfied, so the setup was skipped. Looking at the precondition logs, I only see the probe output (9 pods running) but no apply commands logged, which suggests the apply didn't actually execute. This makes me reconsider what `on_probe_fail: skip` means—maybe it's a guard that prevents the apply from running when the probe succeeds, essentially saying \"only run apply if the probe fails.\"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3158,"cache_read_input_tokens":39093,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3158},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"25f65c27-c4e3-4259-a645-5a43bc6837a5","uuid":"a166cd77-81d1-49ed-8ed9-5757c68d3988","request_id":"req_011CcM1iVVvqu5oHFKF2AYFo"}
